1 Introduction
**************

tmax is a terminal-based text editor designed for software developers,
system administrators, and power users who prefer keyboard-driven
terminal workflows.  It combines the extensibility of Emacs with the
modal editing efficiency of Vim.

   The editor follows a split architecture inspired by GNU Emacs.  A
TypeScript core, running on the Bun runtime (https://bun.sh/), handles
low-level operations: terminal I/O with alternate screen buffer, file
system access, memory management, and display rendering.  All
higher-level editor functionality--commands, modes, key bindings, and
user customization--is implemented in T-Lisp, a built-in Lisp dialect
with tail-call optimization and a macro system.

   tmax has zero external runtime dependencies.  The only requirement is
the Bun runtime itself.

1.1 Key Features
================

   • Modal editing with Vim-style key bindings (hjkl navigation,
     operators, text objects).
   • Five editing modes: normal, insert, visual, command, and M-x.
   • Complete T-Lisp interpreter with lexical scoping, tail-call
     optimization, quasiquote macros, and a standard library of over 30
     built-in functions.
   • Comprehensive editor API with over 100 T-Lisp functions across 35
     API modules.
   • Daemon/client architecture with JSON-RPC 2.0 over Unix sockets,
     supporting multiple simultaneous TUI frames sharing the same
     buffers and interpreter state.
   • Interchangeable frontends: TUI (ANSI escape sequences), Ink
     (React), and Steep.
   • Kill ring with yank-pop cycling, similar to the Emacs kill ring.
   • Built-in help system: ‘describe-key’, ‘describe-function’, and
     ‘apropos-command’.
   • Which-key popup showing available bindings after prefix keys.
   • Plugin system with a TLPA (T-Lisp Package Archive) repository.
   • Keyboard macro recording and playback.
   • LSP diagnostics integration.
   • A ‘*Messages*’ buffer for editor event logging and observability.

1.2 Design Philosophy
=====================

tmax follows the principle of "powerful core, extensible surface."  The
TypeScript core provides efficient, reliable low-level operations, while
T-Lisp provides unlimited customization possibilities.  This
architecture allows users to:

   • Customize editor behavior without recompiling.
   • Create complex macros and commands in T-Lisp.
   • Share configurations as T-Lisp scripts.
   • Extend functionality through a consistent, documented API.


