3 Daemon/Client Architecture
****************************

tmax uses an Emacs-style daemon/client architecture.  A background
daemon process (‘tmax --daemon’) holds all editor state: buffers, the
T-Lisp interpreter, configuration, and the kill ring.  Multiple TUI
clients ("frames") can connect to the same daemon, each with an
independent viewport but sharing the same underlying state.

3.1 Starting the Daemon
=======================

The daemon is the server process that manages all editor state.  It
listens on a Unix domain socket for JSON-RPC 2.0 requests.

     # Start daemon only (no TUI)
     tmax --daemon

   When you run ‘tmax’ without ‘--daemon’, it automatically starts the
daemon if one is not already running, then opens a TUI frame.

     # This auto-starts the daemon if needed
     tmax myfile.txt

3.2 The Unified CLI
===================

The ‘tmax’ command is the primary interface for both daemon and client
operations.

‘tmax [FILE]’
     Start daemon (if not running) and open a TUI frame.  If FILE is
     given, open it in the editor.
‘tmax --daemon’
     Start the daemon only, without opening a TUI frame.
‘tmax -e EXPR’
     Evaluate a T-Lisp expression on the daemon and print the result.
‘tmax --stop’
     Stop the running daemon.
‘tmax -t’
     Open a new terminal frame (this is the default behavior).
‘tmax --init-file PATH’
     Load a custom init file instead of the default
     ‘~/.config/tmax/init.tlisp’.
‘tmax -h’
‘tmax --help’
     Show usage information.

3.3 The Client CLI
==================

The ‘tmaxclient’ command provides direct access to daemon operations
without opening a TUI frame.

‘tmaxclient FILE’
     Open FILE in the daemon.
‘tmaxclient --eval 'CODE'’
     Evaluate T-Lisp code on the daemon.
‘tmaxclient --list-buffers’
     List all open buffers.
‘tmaxclient --kill-buffer NAME’
     Kill (close) a specific buffer.
‘tmaxclient --messages’
     Show the contents of the ‘*Messages*’ buffer.
‘tmaxclient --ping’
     Check whether the daemon is running.
‘tmaxclient --tui’
     Launch the TUI client.
‘tmaxclient --insert TEXT’
     Insert text at the current cursor position.
‘tmaxclient --insert-stdin’
     Read from standard input and insert at the cursor.
‘tmaxclient --script FILE’
     Execute a T-Lisp script file on the daemon.
‘tmaxclient --server-info’
     Query and display full server state.
‘tmaxclient -s PATH’
     Use a custom socket path.
‘tmaxclient -n’
‘tmaxclient --no-wait’
     Open a file without waiting for the buffer to close.

3.4 JSON-RPC 2.0 Protocol
=========================

Clients communicate with the daemon using JSON-RPC 2.0 over a Unix
domain socket.  The default socket path is ‘/tmp/tmax-UID/server’, where
UID is your user ID.

   The protocol supports the following methods:

‘ping’
     Health check.  Returns ‘{"status": "running"}’.
‘open’
     Open a file in the daemon.  Parameters: ‘filepath’, ‘wait’.
‘eval’
     Evaluate T-Lisp code.  Parameters: ‘code’.
‘insert’
     Insert text at the current cursor.  Parameters: ‘text’.
‘command’
     Execute an editor command.  Parameters: ‘command’, plus
     command-specific parameters.
‘query’
     Query server state.  Parameters: ‘query’ (e.g., ‘"full-state"’,
     ‘"messages"’).

3.5 Frames
==========

Each TUI client connected to the daemon is called a “frame”.  Frames
share the same buffers and T-Lisp interpreter but maintain independent
viewports, cursor positions, and scrolling state.  This means you can
have two terminal windows editing different parts of the same file
simultaneously.


