4 Basic Usage
*************

4.1 Starting the Editor
=======================

The recommended way to start tmax is through the unified CLI:

     # Start with a file (auto-starts daemon)
     tmax myfile.txt

     # Start with an empty buffer
     tmax

   For quick editing without the daemon:

     bun run start myfile.txt

4.2 First Steps
===============

When tmax starts, you are in “normal mode”.  The status line at the
bottom of the screen shows the current mode and cursor position.

  1. Press ‘i’ to enter “insert mode” and start typing text.
  2. Press ‘Escape’ to return to normal mode.
  3. Press ‘:’ to enter command mode, type ‘w’, and press ‘Enter’ to
     save the file.
  4. Press ‘:’ to enter command mode, type ‘q’, and press ‘Enter’ to
     quit.
  5. To save and quit in one step, type ‘:wq’ and press ‘Enter’.

4.3 Editing a File
==================

A typical editing workflow:

     tmax myfile.txt    Open a file
     i                  Enter insert mode
     type your text
     Escape             Return to normal mode
     hjkl               Navigate with h, j, k, l
     dd                 Delete a line
     yy                 Yank (copy) a line
     p                  Paste after cursor
     :wq Enter          Save and quit

4.4 The Status Line
===================

The status line at the bottom of the terminal shows:

   • The current editing mode (‘NORMAL’, ‘INSERT’, ‘VISUAL’, ‘COMMAND’,
     or ‘M-X’).
   • The current buffer's major mode, such as ‘[python]’ or
     ‘[fundamental]’.
   • Active minor-mode lighters, such as ‘(Ln Fill)’.
   • The cursor position (line and column).
   • Status messages (e.g., "Saved", "File not found").

   Daemon clients can query the same mode metadata with ‘tmaxclient
--status --json’.  The editor state includes ‘currentMajorMode’,
‘activeMinorModes’, and ‘activeMinorModeLighters’, so UI tests and
client integrations can verify mode behavior without scraping terminal
text.

4.5 The ‘*Messages*’ Buffer
===========================

tmax maintains a special buffer called ‘*Messages*’ that logs editor
events: file operations, mode changes, errors, and T-Lisp evaluation
results.  This buffer is useful for debugging and for monitoring what
the editor is doing.

     :messages         View the Messages buffer (in command mode)
     tmaxclient --messages  View from the command line


