5 Editing Modes
***************

tmax has five editing modes, each with its own key bindings and
behavior.

* Menu:

* Normal Mode::      Navigation and commands.
* Insert Mode::      Entering text.
* Visual Mode::      Selecting text.
* Command Mode::     Vim-style ex commands.
* M-x Mode::        Execute T-Lisp functions by name.


File: tmax.info,  Node: Normal Mode,  Next: Insert Mode,  Up: Editing Modes

5.1 Normal Mode
===============

Normal mode is the default mode when tmax starts.  In this mode,
keystrokes are interpreted as commands rather than text input.  You use
normal mode for navigation, text manipulation, and issuing editor
commands.

   To return to normal mode from any other mode, press ‘Escape’.

   Normal mode supports a “count prefix”: typing a number before a
command repeats the command that many times.  For example, ‘3j’ moves
the cursor down three lines, and ‘5dd’ deletes five lines.


File: tmax.info,  Node: Insert Mode,  Next: Visual Mode,  Prev: Normal Mode,  Up: Editing Modes

5.2 Insert Mode
===============

Insert mode is for entering text directly into the buffer.  Characters
you type are inserted at the cursor position.

   Press ‘i’ to enter insert mode from normal mode.

   Press ‘Escape’ to return to normal mode.

   While in insert mode:

‘Escape’
     Return to normal mode.
‘Backspace’
     Delete the character before the cursor.
‘Enter’
     Insert a newline.
‘Any printable character’
     Insert at cursor position.


File: tmax.info,  Node: Visual Mode,  Next: Command Mode,  Prev: Insert Mode,  Up: Editing Modes

5.3 Visual Mode
===============

Visual mode allows you to select text and then operate on the selection.
tmax supports three types of visual selection:

‘v’
     Character-wise visual selection.  The selection spans from the
     starting cursor position to wherever you move the cursor.
‘V’
     Line-wise visual selection.  Entire lines are selected.
‘C-v’
     Block-wise (rectangular) visual selection.

   While a visual selection is active, you can operate on it:

‘d’
     Delete the selected text.
‘y’
     Yank (copy) the selected text into the kill ring.
‘u’
     Convert the selected text to lowercase.
‘U’
     Convert the selected text to uppercase.
‘Escape’
     Cancel the selection and return to normal mode.


File: tmax.info,  Node: Command Mode,  Next: M-x Mode,  Prev: Visual Mode,  Up: Editing Modes

5.4 Command Mode
================

Command mode provides a command line at the bottom of the screen for
entering Vim-style ex commands.

   Press ‘:’ from normal mode to enter command mode.

‘:w’
     Save the current file.
‘:q’
     Quit the editor.
‘:wq’
     Save and quit.
‘:e FILENAME’
     Open a file for editing.

   Press ‘Enter’ to execute the command.  Press ‘Escape’ to cancel.


File: tmax.info,  Node: M-x Mode,  Prev: Command Mode,  Up: Editing Modes

5.5 M-x Mode
============

M-x mode lets you execute T-Lisp functions by name, similar to the Emacs
‘M-x’ command.  It provides fuzzy command completion.

   Press ‘SPC ;’ (space followed by semicolon) from normal mode to enter
M-x mode.

   Type the name of a T-Lisp function and press ‘Enter’ to execute it.
Examples:

‘cursor-position’
     Display the current cursor position.
‘editor-mode’
     Display the current editing mode.
‘quit’
     Quit the editor.
‘eval-buffer’
     Evaluate the current buffer as T-Lisp code.
‘eval-init-file’
     Reload the init file.

   Press ‘Escape’ to cancel M-x mode without executing a command.


