6 Key Bindings
**************

6.1 Normal Mode Key Bindings
============================

6.1.1 Navigation
----------------

‘h’
     Move cursor left.
‘j’
     Move cursor down.
‘k’
     Move cursor up.
‘l’
     Move cursor right.
‘w’
     Move to the beginning of the next word.
‘b’
     Move to the beginning of the previous word.
‘e’
     Move to the end of the current word.
‘0’
     Move to the beginning of the line.
‘$’
     Move to the end of the line.
‘gg’
     Move to the top of the file.
‘G’
     Move to the bottom of the file.

6.1.2 Mode Switching
--------------------

‘i’
     Enter insert mode.
‘v’
     Enter character-wise visual mode.
‘V’
     Enter line-wise visual mode.
‘C-v’
     Enter block-wise visual mode.
‘:’
     Enter command mode.
‘SPC ;’
     Enter M-x mode.

6.1.3 Editing
-------------

‘dd’
     Delete the current line.
‘yy’
     Yank (copy) the current line.
‘p’
     Paste (put) after the cursor.
‘P’
     Paste (put) before the cursor.
‘x’
     Delete the character under the cursor.
‘dw’
     Delete to the end of the word.
‘cw’
     Change to the end of the word (delete and enter insert mode).
‘u’
     Undo the last change.
‘C-r’
     Redo the last undone change.

6.1.4 Search
------------

‘/’
     Search forward.
‘?’
     Search backward.
‘n’
     Jump to the next search match.

6.1.5 Count Prefix
------------------

Most normal-mode commands accept a numeric count prefix.  Type a number
before the command to repeat it:

‘3j’
     Move down 3 lines.
‘5dd’
     Delete 5 lines.
‘2yy’
     Yank 2 lines.
‘10G’
     Go to line 10.

6.1.6 Other
-----------

‘q’
     Quit the editor (single-file mode, no daemon).

6.2 Insert Mode Key Bindings
============================

‘Escape’
     Return to normal mode.
‘Backspace’
     Delete the character before the cursor.
‘Enter’
     Insert a newline.
‘CHAR’
     Insert the character at cursor position.

6.3 Visual Mode Key Bindings
============================

‘d’
     Delete the selected text.
‘y’
     Yank (copy) the selected text.
‘u’
     Convert selection to lowercase.
‘U’
     Convert selection to uppercase.
‘Escape’
     Cancel selection and return to normal mode.

6.4 Command Mode Key Bindings
=============================

‘TEXT’
     Enter command text.
‘Enter’
     Execute the command.
‘Backspace’
     Delete the last character.
‘Escape’
     Cancel and return to normal mode.

6.5 Custom Key Bindings
=======================

You can define custom key bindings in your init file using the
‘key-bind’ function:

     (key-bind "w" "(cursor-move (+ (cursor-line) 5) (cursor-column))" "normal")
     (key-bind "b" "(cursor-move (- (cursor-line) 5) (cursor-column))" "normal")

   The ‘key-bind’ function takes three arguments:

‘key’
     The key sequence to bind (a string).
‘command’
     The T-Lisp expression to evaluate when the key is pressed (a
     string).
‘mode’
     The mode in which the binding is active: ‘"normal"’, ‘"insert"’,
     ‘"visual"’, ‘"command"’, or ‘"mx"’.

6.6 Which-Key Popup
===================

When you press a prefix key (such as ‘SPC’ or ‘g’), tmax briefly
displays a popup showing all the key bindings that start with that
prefix.  This popup disappears after a configurable timeout (default
1000 milliseconds) or when you press the next key.


