7 Operators and Text Objects
****************************

7.1 Operators
=============

Operators are commands that perform an action on a range of text.  tmax
supports the following operators in normal mode:

‘d’
     Delete operator.  Combined with a motion or text object to delete
     text.  Examples: ‘dd’ (delete line), ‘dw’ (delete word), ‘d$’
     (delete to end of line).
‘y’
     Yank (copy) operator.  Combined with a motion or text object to
     copy text into the kill ring.  Examples: ‘yy’ (yank line), ‘yw’
     (yank word).
‘c’
     Change operator.  Deletes text and enters insert mode.  Examples:
     ‘cw’ (change word), ‘cc’ (change entire line).

7.2 Text Objects
================

Text objects define structural units of text that can be used with
operators.  Text objects come in two forms: “inner” (‘i’) which excludes
surrounding whitespace and delimiters, and “around” (‘a’) which includes
them.

7.2.1 Word Text Object
----------------------

‘diw’
     Delete inner word (the word under the cursor, excluding surrounding
     spaces).
‘daw’
     Delete around word (the word plus surrounding spaces).

7.2.2 Quoted String Text Objects
--------------------------------

‘ci'’
     Change inner single-quoted string.
‘ca'’
     Change around single-quoted string (including the quotes).
‘ci"’
     Change inner double-quoted string.
‘ca"’
     Change around double-quoted string (including the quotes).

7.2.3 Parenthesis and Bracket Text Objects
------------------------------------------

‘di(’
‘di)’
     Delete inner parentheses (contents within parentheses).
‘ci(’
‘ci)’
     Change inner parentheses.
‘di{’
‘di}’
     Delete inner braces (contents within braces).
‘ci{’
‘ci}’
     Change inner braces.
‘di[’
‘di]’
     Delete inner brackets.
‘di<’
     Delete inner angle brackets.
‘dit’
     Delete inner HTML/XML tag.

7.3 Count Prefix with Operators
===============================

Operators support the numeric count prefix to multiply their effect:

‘3dd’
     Delete 3 lines.
‘5dw’
     Delete 5 words.
‘2yy’
     Yank 2 lines.


