8 Search and Replace
********************

8.1 Incremental Search
======================

tmax provides incremental search in normal mode:

‘/PATTERN’
     Search forward for PATTERN.
‘?PATTERN’
     Search backward for PATTERN.
‘n’
     Jump to the next match in the search direction.
‘*’
     Search forward for the word under the cursor.

   When you press ‘/’ or ‘?’, the cursor moves to the command line.
Type your search pattern and press ‘Enter’.  Press ‘Escape’ to cancel
the search.

8.2 Replace Operations
======================

Replace operations are available through the T-Lisp API:

     ;; Start a replace session
     (replace-start "old" "new")

     ;; Replace the current match and move to next
     (replace-next)

     ;; Replace all matches
     (replace-all "old" "new")

8.3 Replace T-Lisp Functions
============================

‘(replace-start FIND REPLACE)’
     Initialize a replace session, finding all occurrences of FIND and
     preparing to replace them with REPLACE.
‘(replace-next)’
     Replace the current match and advance to the next one.
‘(replace-all FIND REPLACE)’
     Replace all occurrences of FIND with REPLACE in the current buffer.
‘(replace-cancel)’
     Cancel the current replace session.
‘(replace-status)’
     Return the current state of the replace session.


File: tmax.info,  Node: Kill Ring,  Next: Buffer Management,  Prev: Search and Replace,  Up: Top

9 Kill Ring
***********

tmax implements an Emacs-style kill ring, a circular buffer that stores
multiple entries of deleted or yanked text.  This is more powerful than
a simple clipboard because you can cycle through previous deletions.

9.1 How the Kill Ring Works
===========================

   • When you delete text (e.g., with ‘dd’, ‘dw’, or visual mode ‘d’),
     the deleted text is added to the front of the kill ring.
   • When you yank with ‘p’ or ‘P’, the most recent entry from the kill
     ring is pasted.
   • Use ‘yank-pop’ to cycle through older entries in the kill ring.
   • The default kill ring size is 5 entries.  When the ring is full,
     the oldest entry is discarded.

9.2 Kill Ring T-Lisp Functions
==============================

‘(kill-ring-add TEXT)’
     Add TEXT to the front of the kill ring.
‘(kill-ring-yank)’
     Return the most recent entry from the kill ring.
‘(kill-ring-rotate)’
     Rotate the kill ring, making the second-most-recent entry the
     current one.  Use this to cycle through previous deletions.
‘(kill-ring-list)’
     Return a list of all entries currently in the kill ring.
‘(kill-ring-size)’
     Return the number of entries in the kill ring.
‘(kill-ring-clear)’
     Remove all entries from the kill ring.

9.3 Yank-Pop
============

After yanking text with ‘p’ or ‘P’, you can cycle through the kill ring
entries by calling ‘(yank-pop)’.  Each invocation replaces the
just-yanked text with the next older entry from the kill ring.

     ;; After pressing p to yank, cycle to the previous kill:
     M-x yank-pop


