10 Buffer Management
********************

tmax supports multiple buffers simultaneously.  Each buffer holds the
contents of a file (or scratch text) and maintains its own cursor
position.

10.1 Opening Buffers
====================

Use command mode to open files into new buffers:

     :e otherfile.txt

   Alternatively, use the T-Lisp API:

     (buffer-create "scratch")
     (buffer-switch "otherfile.txt")

10.2 Switching Buffers
======================

Switch between open buffers using the T-Lisp API:

     (buffer-switch "myfile.txt")

   To list all open buffers from the command line:

     tmaxclient --list-buffers

10.3 Special Buffers
====================

tmax creates several special buffers automatically:

‘*Messages*’
     A log of editor events, T-Lisp evaluations, and status messages.
     Updated continuously as you use the editor.
‘*scratch*’
     A scratch buffer for temporary text and T-Lisp experimentation.
     Use ‘(eval-buffer)’ to evaluate its contents as T-Lisp code.

10.4 Buffer T-Lisp Functions
============================

‘(buffer-create NAME)’
     Create a new empty buffer with the given name.
‘(buffer-switch NAME)’
     Switch to the buffer named NAME.
‘(buffer-current)’
     Return the name of the current buffer.
‘(buffer-list)’
     Return a list of all open buffer names.
‘(buffer-text)’
     Return the full text content of the current buffer.
‘(buffer-line [N])’
     Return the content of line N (or the current line if N is omitted).
‘(buffer-line-count)’
     Return the number of lines in the current buffer.
‘(buffer-insert TEXT)’
     Insert TEXT at the current cursor position.
‘(buffer-delete COUNT)’
     Delete COUNT characters starting at the cursor position.
‘(buffer-save [FILENAME])’
     Save the current buffer to its associated file, or to FILENAME if
     provided.
‘(buffer-save-as FILENAME)’
     Save the current buffer to a new file and update the buffer's
     filename association.
‘(buffer-kill NAME)’
     Kill (close) the buffer named NAME.

10.5 Gap Buffer Implementation
==============================

tmax uses a “gap buffer” data structure for efficient text editing.  A
gap buffer maintains a gap (empty space) at the cursor position, making
insertions and deletions at the cursor O(1) operations.  Moving the
cursor moves the gap, which is an O(n) operation where n is the distance
moved.


