11 Configuration
****************

tmax is configured through T-Lisp scripts.  The primary configuration
file is ‘~/.config/tmax/init.tlisp’, which is loaded automatically when
the editor starts.

11.1 The Init File
==================

Create or edit ‘~/.config/tmax/init.tlisp’ to customize tmax.  This file
is a standard T-Lisp script that runs in the editor's global
environment, so you have access to the full T-Lisp editor API.

   Example init file:

     ;; ~/.config/tmax/init.tlisp

     ;; Custom key bindings
     (key-bind "w" "(cursor-move (+ (cursor-line) 5) (cursor-column))" "normal")
     (key-bind "b" "(cursor-move (- (cursor-line) 5) (cursor-column))" "normal")

     ;; Custom macros
     (defmacro save-and-quit ()
       '(progn
          (file-write (buffer-current) (buffer-text))
          (editor-quit)))

     ;; Custom commands
     (defun center-cursor ()
       (let ((line-count (buffer-line-count))
             (center-line (/ line-count 2)))
         (cursor-move center-line 0)))

     (key-bind "zz" "(center-cursor)" "normal")

11.2 Custom Init File Path
==========================

You can specify a custom init file on the command line:

     tmax --init-file ./my-config.tlisp

   To disable init file loading entirely, use ‘/dev/null’:

     tmax --init-file /dev/null

11.3 Reloading Configuration
============================

To reload your init file without restarting the editor:

     M-x eval-init-file

   Or from the command line:

     tmax -e '(eval-init-file)'

11.4 Evaluating a Buffer
========================

You can evaluate the contents of the current buffer as T-Lisp code:

     M-x eval-buffer

   This is particularly useful with the ‘*scratch*’ buffer for testing
T-Lisp expressions interactively.

11.5 Init File T-Lisp Functions
===============================

‘(init-file-path)’
     Return the path to the current init file.
‘(eval-init-file)’
     Reload and evaluate the init file.
‘(eval-buffer)’
     Evaluate the current buffer's text as T-Lisp code.

11.6 Editor Settings
====================

The editor state includes the following configurable settings:

‘tab-size’
     Tab width for indentation (default: 4).
‘show-line-numbers’
     Whether to display line numbers (default: true).
‘word-wrap’
     Whether to wrap long lines (default: false).
‘max-undo-levels’
     Maximum number of undo levels (default: 100).
‘auto-save’
     Whether to automatically save changes (default: false).

11.7 Macro Recording and Playback
=================================

tmax supports Vim-style keyboard macro recording:

‘qA’
     Start recording a macro into register A (any lowercase letter or
     digit).
‘q’
     Stop recording the macro.
‘@A’
     Execute the macro stored in register A.
‘@@’
     Execute the most recently executed macro again.

   Example workflow:

     qa        Start recording into register a
     jjdd      Move down two lines, delete one
     q         Stop recording
     @a       Replay the macro

11.8 T-Lisp Standard Library
============================

The T-Lisp interpreter includes a standard library of built-in
functions.  These are available in the global environment without any
imports.

11.8.1 Arithmetic
-----------------

‘(+ A B ...)’
     Addition.  Accepts any number of arguments.
‘(- A B ...)’
     Subtraction.
‘(* A B ...)’
     Multiplication.
‘(/ A B)’
     Division.
‘(mod A B)’
     Modulo.
‘(abs N)’
     Absolute value.
‘(sqrt N)’
     Square root.
‘(expt BASE EXP)’
     Exponentiation.
‘(floor N)’
     Floor.
‘(ceiling N)’
     Ceiling.
‘(round N)’
     Round to nearest integer.
‘(min A B ...)’
     Minimum.
‘(max A B ...)’
     Maximum.

11.8.2 Comparison
-----------------

‘(= A B)’
     Numeric equality.
‘(< A B)’
     Less than.
‘(> A B)’
     Greater than.
‘(eq A B)’
     Identity/equality test.

11.8.3 List Operations
----------------------

‘(cons A B)’
     Construct a pair.
‘(car LIST)’
     First element of a list.
‘(cdr LIST)’
     Rest of a list.
‘(list A B ...)’
     Create a list from arguments.
‘(append LIST1 LIST2)’
     Concatenate two lists.
‘(reverse LIST)’
     Reverse a list.
‘(nth N LIST)’
     Return the Nth element of LIST (zero-indexed).
‘(last LIST)’
     Return the last element of LIST.
‘(member ITEM LIST)’
     Return the sublist starting at ITEM, or nil if not found.
‘(length SEQ)’
     Return the length of a list or string.

11.8.4 String Operations
------------------------

‘(substring STR START END)’
     Extract a substring.
‘(string-append A B ...)’
     Concatenate strings.
‘(string= A B)’
     String equality.
‘(string< A B)’
     String less-than (lexicographic).
‘(string> A B)’
     String greater-than (lexicographic).
‘(string-upcase STR)’
     Convert to uppercase.
‘(string-downcase STR)’
     Convert to lowercase.

11.8.5 Predicates
-----------------

‘(null X)’
     True if X is nil.
‘(atom X)’
     True if X is not a pair/list.
‘(numberp X)’
     True if X is a number.
‘(stringp X)’
     True if X is a string.
‘(symbolp X)’
     True if X is a symbol.
‘(listp X)’
     True if X is a list.
‘(functionp X)’
     True if X is a function.
‘(zerop N)’
     True if N is zero.
‘(evenp N)’
     True if N is even.
‘(oddp N)’
     True if N is odd.
‘(not X)’
     Logical negation.

11.8.6 Special Forms
--------------------

‘(quote X)’
     Return X unevaluated.  Abbreviated as ‘'x’.
‘(if COND THEN ELSE)’
     Conditional expression.
‘(let ((VAR1 VAL1) ...) BODY)’
     Local variable bindings.
‘(lambda (PARAMS) BODY)’
     Anonymous function.
‘(defun NAME (PARAMS) BODY)’
     Define a named function.
‘(defmacro NAME (PARAMS) BODY)’
     Define a macro.
‘(progn EXPR1 EXPR2 ...)’
     Evaluate expressions sequentially, return the last result.
‘(cond (TEST1 EXPR1) (TEST2 EXPR2) ...)’
     Multi-branch conditional.

11.8.7 Quasiquote
-----------------

‘`TEMPLATE’
     Quasiquote: construct a list template, evaluating only unquoted
     parts.
‘,EXPR’
     Unquote: evaluate EXPR inside a quasiquote.
‘,@EXPR’
     Unquote-splicing: evaluate EXPR and splice the resulting list into
     the surrounding list.

11.8.8 Hash Maps
----------------

‘(hashmap KEY1 VAL1 ...)’
     Create a hash map from key-value pairs.
‘(hashmap-get MAP KEY)’
     Look up a value by key.  Returns nil if not found.
‘(hashmap-set MAP KEY VAL)’
     Return a new hash map with KEY set to VAL.
‘(hashmap-keys MAP)’
     Return a list of all keys.
‘(hashmap-values MAP)’
     Return a list of all values.
‘(hashmap-has-key? MAP KEY)’
     Return true if MAP contains KEY.

11.8.9 Keymaps
--------------

‘(defkeymap NAME)’
     Define a named keymap.
‘(keymap-define-key KEYMAP KEY BINDING)’
     Bind KEY to BINDING in KEYMAP.
‘(keymap-get KEYMAP KEY)’
     Look up the binding for KEY.
‘(keymap-lookup KEYMAP KEY)’
     Look up a key binding, following parent keymap chains.

11.8.10 I/O
-----------

‘(print X)’
     Print a value to the terminal.


