12 Plugin System
****************

tmax supports a plugin system through the TLPA (T-Lisp Package Archive)
repository.  Plugins are T-Lisp scripts that extend the editor's
functionality.

12.1 Plugin Management
======================

Plugins are managed through T-Lisp functions:

‘(plugin-list)’
     List all available plugins in the TLPA repository.
‘(plugin-show NAME)’
     Show detailed information about a specific plugin.
‘(plugin-install NAME)’
     Install a plugin from the repository.
‘(plugin-search QUERY)’
     Search the repository for plugins matching QUERY.
‘(plugin-info NAME)’
     Return metadata about an installed plugin.

12.2 Plugin Installation Directory
==================================

Installed plugins are stored in ‘~/.config/tmax/tlpa/’.  Each plugin is
a T-Lisp file (or a directory containing a main T-Lisp file) that is
loaded into the editor's T-Lisp environment.

12.3 Available Plugins
======================

The TLPA repository includes plugins such as:

‘theme-solarized’
     Solarized dark color theme for tmax.
‘theme-monokai’
     Monokai color scheme for tmax.
‘lsp-typescript’
     TypeScript language server integration.
‘lsp-python’
     Python language server integration.
‘vim-emulation’
     Additional Vim compatibility bindings.
‘auto-pairs’
     Automatic bracket and quote pairing.

12.4 Creating Plugins
=====================

To create a plugin, write a T-Lisp script that defines functions, key
bindings, and commands.  Place the file in ‘~/.config/tmax/tlpa/’ or
submit it to the TLPA repository.

   A plugin is a standard T-Lisp file.  For example:

     ;; my-plugin.tlisp
     ;; A simple plugin that adds line numbering toggle

     (defun toggle-line-numbers ()
       (let ((current (editor-config "showLineNumbers")))
         (editor-set-config "showLineNumbers"
                            (not current))))

     (key-bind "SPC tn" "(toggle-line-numbers)" "normal")

12.5 Submitting Plugins
=======================

Plugins can be submitted to the TLPA repository for inclusion.  Each
plugin submission includes metadata: name, description, author, version,
license, and optional homepage URL.


