13 Frontends
************

tmax supports multiple interchangeable frontends.  All frontends
communicate with the editor core through the same interface, and the
daemon/client architecture enables remote frontends via JSON-RPC over
Unix sockets.

13.1 TUI Frontend (Default)
===========================

The default frontend is a TUI (Terminal User Interface) client that
renders directly using ANSI escape sequences.  It requires no external
frameworks or dependencies.

   Features:
   • Full-screen interface with alternate screen buffer.
   • Raw mode input with proper key normalization.
   • Viewport management with scrolling for large files.
   • Status line with mode and cursor position.
   • Which-key popup overlay.
   • 200ms state polling when connected to the daemon.

   Start the TUI frontend:

     tmax              Auto-start daemon + TUI
     tmaxclient --tui  Start TUI connected to running daemon
     bun run tui       Start TUI directly

13.2 Ink Frontend (React)
=========================

The Ink frontend uses the Ink (https://github.com/vadimdemedes/ink)
framework (React for the terminal) to render the editor UI as React
components.  This frontend provides a component-based architecture for
more complex UI layouts.

   The Ink frontend is located in ‘src/frontend/’ and uses the same
editor core API as the TUI frontend.

13.3 Steep Frontend
===================

The Steep frontend is an experimental native terminal frontend that
provides an alternative rendering approach.  It is under active
development.

13.4 Selecting a Frontend
=========================

The frontend is determined by how you launch tmax:

   • ‘tmax’ and ‘tmaxclient --tui’ use the TUI frontend.
   • The Ink frontend can be used through the React entry point
     (‘src/main.tsx’).

   All frontends share the same editor core, key bindings, and T-Lisp
environment.  Switching frontends does not affect your configuration or
customization.


