14 Troubleshooting
******************

14.1 The Daemon Will Not Start
==============================

If ‘tmax --daemon’ fails:

   • Check that another tmax daemon is not already running:
          tmaxclient --ping
   • Check for stale socket files:
          ls /tmp/tmax-$(id -u)/
          rm -f /tmp/tmax-$(id -u)/server
   • Check that Bun is installed and on your PATH:
          which bun
          bun --version

14.2 Key Bindings Not Working
=============================

If custom key bindings from your init file are not taking effect:

   • Check the init file for T-Lisp syntax errors:
          bun run repl
          > (load-file "~/.config/tmax/init.tlisp")
   • Reload the init file from within the editor:
          M-x eval-init-file
   • Check the ‘*Messages*’ buffer for error messages:
          tmaxclient --messages

14.3 The Editor Freezes or Does Not Respond
===========================================

   • Make sure you are not in command mode or M-x mode with a pending
     input.  Press ‘Escape’ to return to normal mode.
   • If the TUI client is disconnected from the daemon, restart it:
          tmaxclient --tui
   • As a last resort, stop and restart the daemon:
          tmax --stop
          tmax

14.4 File Encoding Issues
=========================

tmax reads and writes files using UTF-8 encoding.  If you encounter
encoding issues, verify that your terminal is configured for UTF-8:

     echo $LANG
     Should contain "UTF-8"

14.5 Init File Errors
=====================

If the init file contains errors, tmax will log them to the ‘*Messages*’
buffer but will still start.  Check the messages:

     tmaxclient --messages

   To skip the init file entirely:

     tmax --init-file /dev/null

14.6 Getting Help
=================

tmax includes a built-in help system:

‘(describe-key KEY)’
     Show documentation for the command bound to KEY.
‘(describe-function NAME)’
     Show documentation for the T-Lisp function NAME.
‘(apropos-command PATTERN)’
     List all commands matching PATTERN.

   Access these through M-x mode:

     SPC ; describe-key Enter
     SPC ; describe-function Enter
     SPC ; apropos-command Enter


