15 Command Reference
********************

This chapter provides a brief summary of available commands.  For full
documentation of each function, use the built-in help system (*note
Troubleshooting::).

15.1 Editor API Categories
==========================

The T-Lisp editor API is organized into the following modules:

‘Buffer Operations (buffer-ops)’
     Create, switch, query, and manipulate buffers.
‘Cursor Operations (cursor-ops)’
     Move and query the cursor position.
‘Mode Operations (mode-ops)’
     Get and set the editor mode.
‘File Operations (file-ops)’
     Read and write files.
‘Bindings Operations (bindings-ops)’
     Query and manage key bindings.
‘Word Operations (word-ops)’
     Word-level navigation and manipulation.
‘Line Operations (line-ops)’
     Line-level operations.
‘Delete Operations (delete-ops)’
     Delete text and manage the delete register.
‘Yank Operations (yank-ops)’
     Yank text and manage the yank register.
‘Change Operations (change-ops)’
     Change (replace) text.
‘Undo/Redo Operations (undo-redo-ops)’
     Undo and redo editing changes.
‘Count Operations (count-ops)’
     Numeric count prefix for commands.
‘Visual Operations (visual-ops)’
     Visual mode selection management.
‘Text Objects (text-objects-ops)’
     Structural text objects (word, quotes, brackets).
‘Search Operations (search-ops)’
     Forward and backward text search.
‘Replace Operations (replace-ops)’
     Find and replace functionality.
‘Kill Ring (kill-ring)’
     Emacs-style kill ring management.
‘Yank Pop (yank-pop-ops)’
     Cycle through kill ring entries.
‘Jump Operations (jump-ops)’
     Jump to specific positions (top, bottom, line number).
‘Minibuffer Operations (minibuffer-ops)’
     Minibuffer interaction.
‘LSP Diagnostics (lsp-diagnostics)’
     Language server protocol diagnostics.
‘Plugin Operations (plugin-ops)’
     Plugin discovery and management.
‘Documentation (documentation)’
     Help system and documentation lookup.
‘Hook Operations (hook-ops)’
     Event hooks for editor extensibility.
‘Syntax Operations (syntax-ops)’
     Syntax highlighting and analysis.
‘Indent Operations (indent-ops)’
     Automatic indentation.
‘Major Mode Operations (major-mode-ops)’
     Major mode management.
‘Dired Operations (dired-ops)’
     Directory editor functionality.
‘Evil Integration (evil-integration)’
     Vim-emulation compatibility layer.
‘Window Operations (window-ops)’
     Window layout management.
‘Editor State (editor-state)’
     Query and modify editor state.
‘Text Utilities (text-utils)’
     Text manipulation utilities.
‘Keymap Operations (keymap-ops)’
     T-Lisp keymap management.
‘Macro Recording (macro-recording)’
     Keyboard macro recording and playback.
‘Macro Persistence (macro-persistence)’
     Save and load macros to/from files.

15.2 Cursor Functions
=====================

‘(cursor-position)’
     Return the cursor position as a list ‘(LINE COLUMN)’.
‘(cursor-move LINE COLUMN)’
     Move the cursor to the specified line and column.
‘(cursor-line)’
     Return the current line number (zero-indexed).
‘(cursor-column)’
     Return the current column number (zero-indexed).

15.3 Mode Functions
===================

‘(editor-mode)’
     Return the current editor mode as a string.
‘(editor-set-mode MODE)’
     Set the editor mode.  MODE must be one of: ‘"normal"’, ‘"insert"’,
     ‘"visual"’, ‘"command"’, or ‘"mx"’.
‘(editor-status)’
     Return the current status message.
‘(editor-set-status MESSAGE)’
     Set the status line message.
‘(editor-quit)’
     Quit the editor.

15.4 File Functions
===================

‘(file-read FILENAME)’
     Read and return the contents of FILENAME.
‘(file-write FILENAME CONTENT)’
     Write CONTENT to FILENAME.

15.5 LSP Diagnostics Functions
==============================

‘(lsp-diagnostics-list)’
     List all current LSP diagnostics.
‘(lsp-diagnostics-for-line LINE)’
     Return diagnostics for the specified line.
‘(lsp-diagnostics-current-line)’
     Return diagnostics for the current cursor line.
‘(lsp-diagnostics-count)’
     Return diagnostic counts by severity.
‘(lsp-diagnostics-clear)’
     Clear all diagnostics.
‘(lsp-diagnostics-has-errors)’
     Return true if there are any error-level diagnostics.

15.6 Hook Functions
===================

‘(add-hook HOOK-NAME FUNCTION)’
     Add FUNCTION to the named hook.
‘(remove-hook HOOK-NAME FUNCTION)’
     Remove FUNCTION from the named hook.
‘(run-hooks HOOK-NAME)’
     Execute all functions attached to the named hook.

15.7 Testing Framework
======================

The T-Lisp interpreter includes a built-in testing framework:

‘(deftest NAME () BODY)’
     Define a named test.
‘(test-run NAME)’
     Run a specific test.
‘(test-run-all)’
     Run all defined tests.
‘(assert-true EXPR)’
     Assert that EXPR is true.
‘(assert-false EXPR)’
     Assert that EXPR is false.
‘(assert-equal EXPECTED ACTUAL)’
     Assert equality.
‘(assert-not-equal A B)’
     Assert inequality.
‘(assert-error EXPR)’
     Assert that EXPR throws an error.
‘(defvar NAME VALUE)’
     Define a test variable.
‘(set! NAME VALUE)’
     Mutate a variable (only in test context).
‘(deftest-suite NAME () BODY)’
     Define a test suite.

15.8 T-Lisp REPL
================

The T-Lisp REPL (Read-Eval-Print Loop) lets you experiment with T-Lisp
interactively:

     bun run repl

   In the REPL, you can type T-Lisp expressions and see their results
immediately:

     > (+ 1 2 3)
     6
     > (car '(1 2 3))
     1
     > (string-append "hello" " " "world")
     "hello world"
     > (defun square (n) (* n n))
     > (square 7)
     49

   For the complete T-Lisp language and API reference, see the ‘T-Lisp
Reference Manual’ (‘tlisp.info’).


